DirectoryWalk family — performance plan
=======================================

Owner: DirectoryTreeWalker.swift
Scope: SingleDir / Parallel / Run / Schedule / Refilter / Remove
Out of scope: PerformanceLog mechanism, log thresholds, Tree.Traverse.Log, FileTree.Collapse


Measured baseline (perf/perf_report.csv)
----------------------------------------
* DirectoryWalk.SingleDir : 2,852,492 events, total 135,829,464 ms, max 884,237 ms
* DirectoryWalk.Parallel  :        21 calls, avg 630,501 ms, max 1,081,730 ms (~18 min)
* DirectoryWalk.Run       :         6 calls, avg  21,291 ms,  max  92,736 ms
* DirectoryWalk.Schedule  :        43 calls, avg     0.79 ms
* DirectoryWalk.Refilter  :       378 calls, ~0 ms
* DirectoryWalk.Remove    :        36 calls, ~0 ms

Schedule/Refilter/Remove are already cheap. Focus = SingleDir, Parallel, Run.


Root-cause analysis
-------------------
1. Re-walks of the same root.
   The perf log shows the Dropbox "Starbuck Pictures" root being re-walked
   instances 2, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8 within 1.5 min, each taking 18+ min. The
   filter never changed. The current coalescing guard only fires while a
   walk is in-flight; once a walk *finishes* a duplicate scheduleWalk
   blindly re-walks. AppState.reloadDirectoriesFromDisk + FSEvents on
   app-support writes drive this.

2. Recursion is serial below the top level.
   walkParallel only fans out one task per top-level subdir. Inside each
   subtree, walkDir recurses sequentially. On JFK/UX (4910 files) and a
   Dropbox-backed photo root, the long pole is one subtree that has
   thousands of cloud-backed child dirs walked back-to-back. With 24
   cores available the budget is ~19 worker tasks; the current code
   uses up to (top-level-subdir-count) which on a flat root is 1.

3. Per-child .isDirectoryKey re-read.
   walkDir asks contentsOfDirectory(at:, includingPropertiesForKeys:
   [.isDirectoryKey], …) then re-reads .isDirectoryKey via
   resourceValues per child. On a cloud-backed URL the second read can
   re-stat. Switching to a single getResourceValue call with all needed
   keys halves the syscalls on cold dirs.

4. SingleDir event volume = real symptom of #1, #2, #3.
   Each event = one dir walk that crossed 50 ms. 2.85M of them is the
   sum of redundant re-walks (#1) × deep serial subtrees (#2). The
   threshold itself stays (other agent owns log volume).


Code changes
------------
A. Walk-result cache (kills duplicate Runs).
   * Cache key: (root URL, RootFilter, last-modified-of-root-dir).
   * Cache value: WalkResult plus the timestamp the cache was filled.
   * In runWalk, before invoking walkParallel: stat the root, look up
     the cache; if hit AND the root mtime is unchanged AND the filter
     equals the cached filter, reuse the cached tree, skip walkParallel
     entirely, still emit Run start/finish so the audit line is correct.
   * Cache lives on `queue` (same isolation as `roots`). Cleared on
     removeRoot + on a real walk completing.
   * scheduleWalk already coalesces in-flight duplicates. Add a second
     short-circuit: if a fresh cache entry (≤2 s old) exists for the
     same (root, filter), short-circuit without re-walking and just
     re-post didChangeNotification. The FSEvents storm on app-support
     log writes is what is generating these duplicates.

B. Parallel recursion with global concurrency cap (~19).
   * Replace serial walkDir-on-each-child with a recursive walker that
     uses a shared `AsyncSemaphore`-style limiter sized to
     min(19, ProcessInfo.activeProcessorCount * 4 / 5).
   * Top-level (walkParallel) already fans out per top-level subdir.
     Extend: any subtree whose listed-dir-child count > 1 also fans out
     via withTaskGroup, gated by the limiter so total in-flight tasks
     across the whole walk stay ≤ 19.
   * Single-dir branches (only one child dir) recurse inline — no task
     overhead.
   * Lex order at each level is preserved by indexed slot writes
     (same pattern as the existing top-level code).

C. Single getResourceValue call per child.
   * Replace `try? entry.resourceValues(forKeys: [.isDirectoryKey])`
     per child with the prefetch already attached to URLs returned by
     `contentsOfDirectory(at:includingPropertiesForKeys:)`. The URLs
     come with cached values; read via
     `(entry as NSURL).getResourceValue(_:forKey:)` once. Same data,
     no extra stat on cloud roots.

D. Stay-serial paths.
   * refilter / refilterAll / removeRoot remain queue-serial.
   * Small (<= 16 entries) directories don't fan out — task spawn cost
     exceeds the walk.
   * The MCP single-file refresh path (no API change here) stays serial.

E. Cancellation discipline.
   * Keep the existing Task.isCancelled check in walkDir / walkParallel.
   * The new recursive task-group walker also checks Task.isCancelled
     before each fan-out so a superseded walk dies quickly on a deep
     cloud tree.


What stays parallel vs serial (user rule)
-----------------------------------------
* PARALLEL (mass walk only):
  - walkParallel and the new recursive task-group walker behind it.
  - Top-of-stack scheduleWalk → runWalk → walkParallel.
* SERIAL:
  - Cache lookups (queue.async, microsecond cost).
  - refilter / refilterAll (in-memory only).
  - removeRoot.
  - Small subtrees (≤ 16 entries) inside the walker.


Validation
----------
1. `cd code && swift build` — must compile clean.
2. `cd code && swift test --filter DirectoryTree` if quick.
3. Re-trace expectation:
   * SingleDir count: 2.85M → ≤ 500k (cache hits skip most re-walks;
     parallel recursion drops per-dir wall time below the 50 ms
     log threshold on local SSD trees).
   * Total SingleDir ms: 135M → ≤ 30M (≈ 75% reduction).
   * Parallel avg: 630s → ≤ 60s on cache hit, ≤ 250s on cold cloud
     walk (limiter, single-stat children).
   * Run avg: 21s → ≤ 8s.
* Schedule/Refilter/Remove unchanged (already trivial).


Follow-ups deferred
-------------------
* Per-subdirectory mtime cache (would let a refresh skip unchanged
  subtrees, not just unchanged roots). Larger surface — a separate pass.
* Lazy children loading on FileTree expand. Owned by another agent.


Completion log
--------------
State on arrival: code/Sources/ImageGlassCore/FileList/DirectoryTreeWalker.swift
had already been implemented to spec in commit 810da07 ("Bryan 20") —
the +228 lines for this file in that commit cover items A through E:

  * WalkCacheEntry struct + walkCache dictionary (item A).
  * scheduleWalk cache-hit short-circuit at ≤ 2 s with matching root
    mtime + filter (item A).
  * runWalk cache lookup before walkParallel + cache write after
    a real walk completes (item A).
  * walkCache + inflightFilter cleared in removeRoot (item A).
  * Recursive walkSubtreeParallel with TaskGroup fan-out (item B).
  * WalkLimiter actor with non-blocking tryAcquire/release so a
    parent task holding a slot never deadlocks waiting on a child
    that cannot get one — falls back to serial walkDir for the
    losing subtree (item B).
  * maxParallelWalkers = max(1, min(19, cores * 4 / 5)) (item B).
  * minChildrenToFanOut = 2 — single-subdir levels recurse inline
    rather than spawn a TaskGroup whose overhead would dominate
    (item D, narrower than the plan's "<= 16 entries" but matches
    item B's "listed-dir-child count > 1 also fans out"; the tighter
    rule wins because subdir-spawn cost is what we are amortizing
    over, not file-classification cost which is already inline).
  * .isDirectoryKey read once per child via the
    contentsOfDirectory(at:includingPropertiesForKeys:) prefetch
    (item C).
  * refilter / refilterAll / removeRoot stay queue.sync (item D).
  * Task.isCancelled checked at every fan-out point (item E).

