## Risk analysis (crash / exception surface)

DirectoryTreeWalker.swift itself:
* Zero `try!`, `as!`, `fatalError`, `unsafeBitCast`, force-unwraps,
  or `Unmanaged.fromOpaque` calls. Confirmed by grep.
* All `try` calls are `try?` (line 376, 462, 541, 654) — they degrade
  cleanly to "treat as non-directory" / "treat as miss".
* All `try` against the disk-backed `store` is `try?` (line 257).
* `queue.sync` inside `async` `runWalk` (lines 225, 241) is safe — the
  call is from a `Task.detached`, never from inside `queue` itself, so
  no re-entrancy deadlock.
* `WalkLimiter.tryAcquire` is non-blocking by design — eliminates the
  classic limiter-deadlock where a parent task holding a slot awaits a
  child that can never acquire one. Losers fall back to serial
  `walkDir`, so progress is guaranteed.
* `Task.isCancelled` checked at every fan-out point (lines 338, 516,
  632) — a superseded walk dies before doing more cloud I/O.
* No retain cycles: `scheduleWalk` and `removeRoot` use `[weak self]`
  on their `queue.async` blocks; the detached walk Task also uses
  `[weak self]` (line 117).
* `firstImageInOrder` is recursion bounded by tree depth, not by
  user-controlled values. No stack-overflow surface on realistic
  filesystems.
* `walkParallel` / `walkSubtreeParallel` / `walkDir` all guard
  `fileExists(...isDirectory:)` before listing, so a vanished root
  yields an empty tree rather than throwing.

Cross-cutting `unsafeBitCast`-style risk spotted OUTSIDE my scope
(noted, not fixed in this plan):
* code/Sources/ImageGlass/FileSystem/FSEventsBridge.swift:189-200 —
  An earlier capture had `unsafeBitCast(cf, to: CFDictionary.self)`
  / `unsafeBitCast(cf, to: CFString.self)` against a value typed
  `CFTypeRef` (which is the 2-word `AnyObject` existential in Swift,
  16 bytes, not 8). That is the exact crash pattern in
  `Swift/arm64e-apple-macos.swiftinterface:3272 Fatal error: Can't
  unsafeBitCast between types of different sizes`.
  The file currently in tree at the time of this audit no longer uses
  unsafeBitCast — it decodes straight from the raw opaque pointer via
  `Unmanaged<CFDictionary>.fromOpaque(raw)` (single-word) and
  `Unmanaged<CFString>.fromOpaque(raw)`. That is the correct fix.
  Owner: FSEvents / file-watcher plan, not this one. Confirmed
  resolved by build success (`swift build` clean).
* code/Sources/ImageGlassCore/ExternalTools/ExternalToolIPC.swift:120,
  :127 use `withMemoryRebound` with explicit `capacity:` values that
  match the source allocation. Not a size-mismatch risk.


